WEBVTT

00:00.734 --> 00:03.103
Narrator: Tonight,
it's Sharkoween in the Tank,

00:03.103 --> 00:05.305
and scarier than ever.
[ Wolf howls ]

00:05.305 --> 00:07.441
And Jason Blum,
the King of Horror

00:07.441 --> 00:11.078
and the founder of game-changing
production company Blumhouse,

00:11.078 --> 00:12.212
joins the Tank.

00:12.212 --> 00:13.981
I have a lot
of scary experience.

00:13.981 --> 00:15.015
Why are you here?

00:15.015 --> 00:16.884
We're full-time
professional weirdos.

00:16.884 --> 00:17.584
Yeah, baby.

00:17.584 --> 00:20.354
Who's ready to raise
the dead with me?
We are!

00:20.354 --> 00:22.356
In the spirit of Halloween,
I came here to get a deal.

00:22.356 --> 00:24.291
-Are you making any money?
-No.

00:24.291 --> 00:27.027
-You are a very brave man.
-Are you getting creepy?

00:27.027 --> 00:29.897
[ Transylvanian accent ]
Very, very scary.

00:35.269 --> 00:37.971
Ooh, I love how scary it is
in the Tank.

00:37.971 --> 00:39.106
It's going to get scarier.

00:39.106 --> 00:41.074
-Ooh! I'm excited.
-Oh, boy.

00:41.074 --> 00:43.710
I love it!
I love it.

00:43.710 --> 00:45.212
♪♪

00:45.212 --> 00:47.381
Narrator: First in the Tank
is an entrepreneur

00:47.381 --> 00:50.951
in the business
of chills and thrills.

00:50.951 --> 00:57.157
♪♪

00:57.157 --> 00:59.259
[ Thunder cracks ]

00:59.259 --> 01:00.460
Hello, Sharks.

01:00.460 --> 01:03.964
My name is Guy Kitchell,
and I'm a serial thriller

01:03.964 --> 01:05.432
from Madison, Wisconsin,

01:05.432 --> 01:08.135
and the CEO of Thrill Builders.

01:08.135 --> 01:09.970
[ Wolf howls ]

01:09.970 --> 01:12.973
I'm seeking $250,000

01:12.973 --> 01:15.442
for a 20% share in my company.

01:15.442 --> 01:17.611
Sharks, Thrill Builders
has created

01:17.611 --> 01:20.480
some of the greatest attractions
for the largest names

01:20.480 --> 01:24.217
in the industry --
everything from escape rooms,

01:24.217 --> 01:28.021
mini golf, animated props,
haunted attractions,

01:28.021 --> 01:29.222
and special effects.

01:29.222 --> 01:30.390
We're the best in the biz

01:30.390 --> 01:34.127
when it comes to all things
thrill-inducing.

01:34.127 --> 01:36.196
Now, I love Halloween,

01:36.196 --> 01:40.434
but the problem is
it only happens one day a year.

01:40.434 --> 01:42.336
Why can't it be every day?

01:42.336 --> 01:44.438
Well, that's where
Thrill Builders comes in.

01:44.438 --> 01:46.640
We're building Thrill Factory,

01:46.640 --> 01:50.444
a 50,000-square-foot
indoor entertainment center

01:50.444 --> 01:53.313
for adults and kids
that actually rocks.

01:53.313 --> 01:54.448
[ Squeaking ]

01:54.448 --> 01:58.986
Thrill Factory will have
12 amazing activities,

01:58.986 --> 02:00.320
like Wizard's Adventure,

02:00.320 --> 02:03.390
where kids will use real
magic wands to solve puzzles

02:03.390 --> 02:06.994
and explore
the Enchanted Forest,

02:06.994 --> 02:07.661
or Hyper Bowling,

02:07.661 --> 02:11.098
where interactive bumpers
allow you to score points

02:11.098 --> 02:12.265
by hitting the moving targets.

02:12.265 --> 02:17.204
And, of course, our signature
haaaaunted houses

02:17.204 --> 02:20.107
that let you blast
animatronic monsters

02:20.107 --> 02:22.309
as you navigate a haunted maze.

02:22.309 --> 02:25.312
Our activities
are a barrel of fun.

02:25.312 --> 02:28.415
-[ Laughs ]
-Oh, wow.

02:28.415 --> 02:30.617
Thrill Factory will be
fully immersive,

02:30.617 --> 02:34.154
with attention to detail
and incredible theming

02:34.154 --> 02:36.223
like only Thrill Builders
can do.

02:36.223 --> 02:39.292
We know what works,
we know what people like,

02:39.292 --> 02:41.428
and we know what makes
the most money.

02:41.428 --> 02:46.466
So, Sharks, who's ready
to raise the dead with me

02:46.466 --> 02:50.837
and build the next big thing
in family entertainment?

02:51.571 --> 02:54.408
Well, you other Sharks
may not know this,

02:54.408 --> 02:58.111
but we have had
a Blumhouse of Horrors,

02:58.111 --> 03:00.147
which is a live-event
haunted house

03:00.147 --> 03:01.248
for many, many years.

03:01.248 --> 03:04.251
They're very, very hard
to make money at.

03:04.251 --> 03:05.652
So my hat's off to you.

03:05.652 --> 03:09.623
I'd love to know a little bit
more about your numbers

03:09.623 --> 03:12.225
that you achieved
in the earlier haunted houses

03:12.225 --> 03:13.360
that you've already done.

03:13.360 --> 03:14.661
Yeah, so we've only done
one haunted house.

03:14.661 --> 03:17.197
It was called
Wisconsin Scary Land.

03:17.197 --> 03:18.432
And you're right --

03:18.432 --> 03:20.300
haunted houses
don't make a lot of money...

03:20.300 --> 03:21.334
[ Laughs ]
No problem.

03:21.334 --> 03:22.569
...which is why
we're moving into

03:22.569 --> 03:25.639
family entertainment centers,
which do make a ton of money.

03:25.639 --> 03:28.575
But our haunted house,
we had 68 actors,

03:28.575 --> 03:30.310
so that ate up
most of our budget.

03:30.310 --> 03:31.445
How many nights
was it open?

03:31.445 --> 03:33.413
We were only open 11 nights,
so you're right.

03:33.413 --> 03:36.249
You make a couple hundred
thousand bucks for the season.

03:36.249 --> 03:37.718
And how much did you spend?
About that?

03:37.718 --> 03:41.588
No, we probably grossed about
450 and netted under 2.

03:41.588 --> 03:44.324
Oh, that's -- I mean,
that's impressive.
Well, you netted --

03:44.324 --> 03:46.426
Did better than me.
My hat's off to you.

03:46.426 --> 03:47.561
We've owned our own
haunted house.

03:47.561 --> 03:49.496
We've owned our own
escape-room complex,

03:49.496 --> 03:51.331
small family-entertainment
center,

03:51.331 --> 03:53.366
and now we're building
a big-scale one,

03:53.366 --> 03:54.534
a 50,000-square-foot one.

03:54.534 --> 03:55.669
And are you buying
a building,

03:55.669 --> 03:57.471
renting a building,
leasing a building?

03:57.471 --> 03:59.172
How much are you gonna
have to invest in total?

03:59.172 --> 04:00.407
'Cause that does
not sound cheap.

04:00.407 --> 04:03.543
No, our current project
is in a mall,

04:03.543 --> 04:07.147
and in the 50,000 square feet,

04:07.147 --> 04:09.449
our GC work is $1.8 million,

04:09.449 --> 04:11.818
and then the whole project
will be $7.2 million.

04:11.818 --> 04:14.221
Where's that money
coming from?
Corcoran and Greiner: Wow.

04:14.221 --> 04:17.424
So we've raised
$1.7 million in cash,

04:17.424 --> 04:21.428
and I have a loan for $5 million
backed by the SBA.

04:21.428 --> 04:24.231
You are a very brave man.
Very brave.

04:24.231 --> 04:25.532
Or you're nuts,
one or the other.

04:25.532 --> 04:27.467
How much money
are you expecting to make?

04:27.467 --> 04:31.371
We project to gross $5.5 mil
the first year...

04:31.371 --> 04:32.539
Really?
...and ramp that up
to $10 mil.

04:32.539 --> 04:35.342
And are you selling
merchandise and food?

04:35.342 --> 04:36.510
And what else
are you doing?

04:36.510 --> 04:38.311
Can I do
a birthday party there?

04:38.311 --> 04:39.780
We have birthday parties.
We have bowling.

04:39.780 --> 04:42.215
Hyper bowling is new.
It's for little kids.

04:42.215 --> 04:43.416
It's got 200 different games

04:43.416 --> 04:45.152
that you can play
with the bumpers.

04:45.152 --> 04:46.319
What's your ticket price?

04:46.319 --> 04:48.355
There's no ticket price
to get in.
No?

04:48.355 --> 04:49.456
It's just per-attraction.

04:49.456 --> 04:51.758
Let me get this deal --
$250,000 for 20%.

04:51.758 --> 04:54.327
Am I getting a piece
of your existing business

04:54.327 --> 04:56.163
selling scary stuff
to other guys,

04:56.163 --> 04:57.664
or just this facility?

04:57.664 --> 04:59.566
This is a real-estate play
in some ways.

04:59.566 --> 05:01.501
I'm open to either.
So our existing business,

05:01.501 --> 05:05.338
Thrill Builders, will do
$4.2 million this year in sales.
Yeah.

05:05.338 --> 05:08.475
We did 3.2 last year,
and we've done

05:08.475 --> 05:10.510
in the last six years
$12.2 million.

05:10.510 --> 05:13.413
And it's profitable, too.
What did you make
last year?

05:13.413 --> 05:15.816
Last year, we made
$975,000 profit.

05:15.816 --> 05:18.585
Blum: And do you own 100%
of your business now?

05:18.585 --> 05:22.322
No, I've sold 17%
to get the $1.7 million.
Got it.

05:22.322 --> 05:25.325
Guy, let me just clear
the deck a little.

05:25.325 --> 05:26.459
I'm going to go out,

05:26.459 --> 05:27.627
and it's not that
I don't believe in you.

05:27.627 --> 05:29.362
And I imagine
you'll do very well.

05:29.362 --> 05:31.398
And there are good numbers
associated with it,

05:31.398 --> 05:32.699
but it would scare
the heck out of me.

05:32.699 --> 05:36.136
I don't know a thing about it.
So for that reason, I'm out.

05:36.136 --> 05:37.337
All right, thank you.

05:37.337 --> 05:40.640
Well, I'm happy to say,
if it sweetens the pot,

05:40.640 --> 05:43.443
I'm happy to have
all of your investment

05:43.443 --> 05:44.711
secured by Thrill Builders,

05:44.711 --> 05:46.546
and I understand
you're taking a risk.

05:46.546 --> 05:47.647
O'Leary: Well, I think
I would need that.

05:47.647 --> 05:48.748
I mean, I'm intrigued.
I have nothing like this

05:48.748 --> 05:50.650
in my portfolio.
I love real estate.

05:50.650 --> 05:52.786
It's funny -- I actually
like the business

05:52.786 --> 05:55.822
that he had
before the event.
Right.

05:55.822 --> 05:58.892
Seems to me like you're biting
off way more than you can chew,

05:58.892 --> 06:01.728
but I don't have
any real-estate experience.

06:01.728 --> 06:03.763
I have a lot
of scary experience,

06:03.763 --> 06:06.766
so if there was some way
to get ownership

06:06.766 --> 06:08.868
of your core business,
that's actually

06:08.868 --> 06:10.637
very interesting to me.
Well, he's willing
to guarantee.

06:10.637 --> 06:12.839
But I want a piece
of the whole thing.

06:12.839 --> 06:16.676
Well, I love it. I do.
I love it. I can see it.

06:16.676 --> 06:19.613
I think you need to make this
for kids and adults.

06:19.613 --> 06:20.714
There's something
for everyone, right?

06:20.714 --> 06:22.582
All right, Guy, listen.
I -- no. Stop. Wait.

06:22.582 --> 06:24.517
I'm gonna make an offer.
I'm gonna make an offer.
Whoa! Whoa!

06:24.517 --> 06:26.553
I'm gonna make an offer.
Whoa, Nelly!

06:26.553 --> 06:30.190
♪♪

06:34.728 --> 06:37.731
Narrator: One Shark is out,
but Kevin, Lori, and Jason

06:37.731 --> 06:40.600
seem interested in Guy's
scary entertainment company,

06:40.600 --> 06:41.835
Thrill Builders.

06:41.835 --> 06:44.337
O'Leary: I think it's an
interesting play on real estate.

06:44.337 --> 06:47.407
I'll do the $250,000
for 25%.

06:47.407 --> 06:48.575
I'm willing to do
the whole thing myself

06:48.575 --> 06:49.743
or split it with anybody
who wants to split.

06:49.743 --> 06:51.745
I do want to do
a deal with you...

06:51.745 --> 06:53.446
But it's the whole business.
...because I love it.

06:53.446 --> 06:54.648
Yeah, the whole business.

06:54.648 --> 06:57.651
I would like to do
the $250,000.

06:57.651 --> 07:00.654
I would do it for 25%.

07:00.654 --> 07:02.922
How about three Sharks?

07:02.922 --> 07:06.760
Between me and Blumhouse,
we have 3 million followers.

07:06.760 --> 07:10.430
And on getting people who love
scary stuff to your events,

07:10.430 --> 07:11.798
we're pretty good at that.

07:11.798 --> 07:13.533
-Well...
-I mean, you can't go wrong.

07:13.533 --> 07:14.701
...each with
a different specialty

07:14.701 --> 07:15.735
You've got --
between the three of us,

07:15.735 --> 07:16.770
you've got everything
covered here.

07:16.770 --> 07:20.874
And you're raising
from 20% to 25%?

07:20.874 --> 07:24.311
Well, if it's three Sharks,
you gotta give us 30

07:24.311 --> 07:26.913
so it's 10 each.

07:26.913 --> 07:30.583
Could you work out a line
of credit for our next opening?

07:30.583 --> 07:33.286
Well, I'm interested
in going to finance this.

07:33.286 --> 07:34.754
If these numbers are real,

07:34.754 --> 07:38.658
you're gonna come with me
to some foreign countries.

07:38.658 --> 07:40.627
I've always wanted
to go to Dubai, so...

07:40.627 --> 07:43.563
No, because that's what I do.
That's why I'm interested.

07:43.563 --> 07:44.831
Guy, your numbers
don't add up, then,

07:44.831 --> 07:47.734
because you said
you made $970,000

07:47.734 --> 07:49.569
from Thrill Builders,
right?

07:49.569 --> 07:51.571
That's in one year?
Or is that lifetime?

07:51.571 --> 07:54.674
No, that was our net
off of $3.2 mil.

07:54.674 --> 07:55.809
-Last year, right?
-Yeah.

07:55.809 --> 07:58.812
So let's just make it $1 million
to simplify it.

07:58.812 --> 08:03.583
So for $250,000 for 30%,
you're gonna write them a check

08:03.583 --> 08:05.418
at the end of the year
for $300,000

08:05.418 --> 08:06.886
for giving you $250,000.

08:06.886 --> 08:09.556
I know I'm undervaluing
the company,

08:09.556 --> 08:11.858
but it's very important to me
that I get a deal.

08:11.858 --> 08:14.694
Guy, why is it so important
you get a deal from a Shark?

08:14.694 --> 08:16.863
I don't get that at these terms.
I don't understand.

08:16.863 --> 08:19.332
Well, it's not the money
for this one.

08:19.332 --> 08:20.000
It's for expansion.

08:20.000 --> 08:22.002
I want to build nine of these
in the next five years.

08:22.002 --> 08:24.571
That's the part I like.
So if you had this one --

08:24.571 --> 08:25.739
Right. You guys, why are
you such naysayers?

08:25.739 --> 08:27.006
You're throwing away
your business, Guy.

08:27.006 --> 08:29.809
Do the math.
All right, I'm restating
the deal here...

08:29.809 --> 08:31.778
Blum: They're trying to
unsell our deal here.

08:31.778 --> 08:33.913
I'm not trying to go in.
I'm trying to help the guy.

08:33.913 --> 08:36.750
Greiner: Okay, so it's
the three of us.

08:36.750 --> 08:41.921
It's $250,000,
30% for the entire business.

08:41.921 --> 08:44.758
And we'll be in it to win it
with you together.

08:44.758 --> 08:46.926
What do you think?
This is so exciting.
I'm interested.

08:46.926 --> 08:50.697
All right, so you want to
raise it to 30%, 10% each.

08:50.697 --> 08:52.532
Will you go to $300,000 then?

08:52.532 --> 08:53.800
-I'd do that.
-I would do that.

08:53.800 --> 08:56.403
-I would do that.
-All right. Let's make a deal.

08:56.403 --> 08:58.805
Whoo! Okay. Yay!

08:58.805 --> 08:59.906
I'm so excited.
I love this!

08:59.906 --> 09:02.075
-Oh, we're gonna hug.
-Yes! I'm thrilled.

09:02.075 --> 09:03.877
-I'm gonna give you a hug, too.
-All right. Thank you.

09:03.877 --> 09:06.813
-Great job, great job.
-I think it's so smart.

09:06.813 --> 09:11.017
He just gave away 30%
of his company for nothing.

09:11.017 --> 09:13.853
Remember the watermelon?
The watermelon and the grape?

09:13.853 --> 09:15.722
-Exactly, Mark.
-That's right.

09:15.722 --> 09:16.756
But the watermelon
and the grape --

09:16.756 --> 09:18.491
You know what?
Mark always does this

09:18.491 --> 09:19.893
when he doesn't
get a deal...

09:19.893 --> 09:21.728
-'Cause I didn't get the deal?
-He's upset.

09:21.728 --> 09:23.630
-Yes! Jelly.
-No, I'm not upset.

09:23.630 --> 09:26.566
This is Mark
waiting for a deal.

09:26.566 --> 09:27.767
Thank you, everybody.

09:27.767 --> 09:29.769
Do I want to give up 30%?

09:29.769 --> 09:33.039
No, but I see the bigger picture
of Thrill Factory.

09:33.039 --> 09:35.775
Rather than capping out
our current business

09:35.775 --> 09:37.076
at $5 or $6 million a year,

09:37.076 --> 09:40.013
we're gonna be doing over
$100 million a year.

09:40.013 --> 09:42.115
And I'd much rather
have those Sharks on board

09:42.115 --> 09:44.884
and give up a portion to them
to make that happen.

09:44.884 --> 09:47.620
[ Transylvanian accent ]
Very, very scary.

09:47.620 --> 09:49.389
Yes, for him.

09:50.723 --> 09:53.026
I was born
in Los Angeles in 1969.

09:53.026 --> 09:55.795
My mother is a retired professor
of art history.

09:55.795 --> 09:57.964
My father started
an art gallery.

09:57.964 --> 10:00.800
My father took risks
by buying paintings from artists

10:00.800 --> 10:02.669
that no one heard of
and no one liked.

10:02.669 --> 10:05.605
I watched my dad take risks
as an entrepreneur,

10:05.605 --> 10:06.706
which paid off for him,

10:06.706 --> 10:09.809
and it deeply affected
my professional path.

10:09.809 --> 10:11.578
My first job out of school,

10:11.578 --> 10:13.746
I sold cable television
door to door.

10:13.746 --> 10:15.048
Turned out I was
a very good salesman.

10:15.048 --> 10:18.051
And in a way, what I still do
is primarily sales.

10:18.051 --> 10:21.688
My second job -- by day
I was a real-estate agent,

10:21.688 --> 10:22.956
and at night
I was producing theater.

10:22.956 --> 10:24.991
I got together with
a group called Malaparte,

10:24.991 --> 10:27.727
run by Ethan Hawke,
and I had this amazing group

10:27.727 --> 10:29.829
of colleagues
at a very young age.

10:29.829 --> 10:31.097
My first official job
in entertainment

10:31.097 --> 10:33.700
was working as vice president
of acquisitions

10:33.700 --> 10:34.801
for Arrow Entertainment.

10:34.801 --> 10:37.570
In 1996,
I went to the big leagues,

10:37.570 --> 10:38.571
which is Miramax.

10:38.571 --> 10:39.906
When I got to my late 20s,

10:39.906 --> 10:42.075
I started my own company,
but after two and a half years,

10:42.075 --> 10:44.010
that company completely
went down the tubes.

10:44.010 --> 10:45.845
I almost went to go work
for somebody else.

10:45.845 --> 10:46.913
But something in me says,

10:46.913 --> 10:48.548
"You have to do this
on your own,"

10:48.548 --> 10:49.782
and out of the sky,

10:49.782 --> 10:51.784
I got a first-look deal
at Paramount.

10:51.784 --> 10:53.887
I got money to keep
my company running,

10:53.887 --> 10:57.023
and that was really
the beginning of Blumhouse.

10:57.023 --> 10:59.659
"Paranormal Activity" was
the movie that changed my life.

10:59.659 --> 11:01.694
Every studio had passed
on the movie,

11:01.694 --> 11:02.929
and I called the filmmaker,
and I said,

11:02.929 --> 11:05.064
"Let me try and get this movie
into movie theaters.

11:05.064 --> 11:09.035
And if you make anything over
$500,000, I want X percent."

11:09.035 --> 11:10.770
The budget of
"Paranormal Activity"

11:10.770 --> 11:11.971
was $15,000,

11:11.971 --> 11:15.508
and the movie wound up
grossing $193 million.

11:15.508 --> 11:16.109
We made six

11:16.109 --> 11:17.944
"Paranormal Activity" movies
after that.

11:17.944 --> 11:20.680
The total worldwide gross
of all seven movies

11:20.680 --> 11:22.015
is approaching $1 billion.

11:22.015 --> 11:24.184
What "Paranormal Activity"
did for me was teach me

11:24.184 --> 11:26.853
that there was a way
to make independent movies

11:26.853 --> 11:28.988
that could be
incredibly lucrative,

11:28.988 --> 11:30.757
and the way we do that
is we make

11:30.757 --> 11:32.125
very, very low-budgeted movies,

11:32.125 --> 11:34.794
and we own a big piece
of the revenue

11:34.794 --> 11:36.129
because we've worked
for nothing up front.

11:36.129 --> 11:39.032
We and the director and the
actors don't get paid up front.

11:39.032 --> 11:41.134
If the movies work,
everyone does very, very well,

11:41.134 --> 11:42.969
and if they don't,
no one gets too hurt

11:42.969 --> 11:44.037
because the movies didn't cost

11:44.037 --> 11:45.638
very much money
in the first place.

11:45.638 --> 11:46.739
It was a new model.

11:46.739 --> 11:48.942
It was a different approach
to making movies.

11:48.942 --> 11:50.143
One of the proudest moments
I had

11:50.143 --> 11:53.746
was when Harvard asked to do
a case study on Blumhouse.

11:53.746 --> 11:54.948
When we did that case study,

11:54.948 --> 11:57.750
we had 13 of the top 25

11:57.750 --> 11:59.986
most profitable movies
ever made.

11:59.986 --> 12:02.021
Can we get like 10%
out of the budget?

12:02.021 --> 12:03.957
Blumhouse is
a multimedia company.

12:03.957 --> 12:06.059
We do massive
horror franchises --

12:06.059 --> 12:08.761
"The Exorcist,"
"Halloween," "M3GAN."

12:08.761 --> 12:11.331
We've been able to reach
outside of horror --

12:11.331 --> 12:14.067
"Whiplash," for which we were
nominated for an Academy Award.

12:14.067 --> 12:15.835
We were nominated
for Best Picture

12:15.835 --> 12:16.936
for "BlacKkKlansman,"

12:16.936 --> 12:19.606
the ultimate horror movie,
"Get Out."

12:19.606 --> 12:20.807
I'm always afraid of failure,

12:20.807 --> 12:23.610
but you can't be
an entrepreneur and not fail.

12:23.610 --> 12:24.677
No, we need it sooner than that.

12:24.677 --> 12:25.878
It's got to be ready
by Halloween.

12:25.878 --> 12:27.981
I've been a fan of "Shark Tank"
for a long time.

12:27.981 --> 12:29.082
It's an incredibly
important show

12:29.082 --> 12:31.150
because I think people
almost watch "Shark Tank"

12:31.150 --> 12:33.219
in the same way
they watch the Academy Awards.

12:33.219 --> 12:35.788
Someone always says,
"I remember when I was little

12:35.788 --> 12:37.023
and I watched
the Academy Awards, I thought,

12:37.023 --> 12:40.059
someday I'll make it
to this stage."

12:40.059 --> 12:42.996
And I think "Shark Tank"
is a very similar thing.

12:42.996 --> 12:45.798
It gives people hope that, like,
"Hey, if they did it,

12:45.798 --> 12:47.467
I can do it, too."

12:47.467 --> 12:51.437
♪♪

12:56.809 --> 12:58.745
♪♪

12:58.745 --> 13:01.681
[ Evil laughing ]

13:01.681 --> 13:03.850
[ Creaking ]

13:03.850 --> 13:05.818
Narrator:
Next up is a healthier version

13:05.818 --> 13:08.221
of a sweet-and-spicy
Mexican treat.

13:08.221 --> 13:11.724
[ Playing mariachi
"Shark Tank" music ]

13:11.724 --> 13:17.897
♪♪

13:17.897 --> 13:24.070
♪♪

13:24.070 --> 13:26.706
Sounds cool with a band,
doesn't it?

13:26.706 --> 13:29.208
♪♪

13:29.208 --> 13:31.778
Hola, Sharks.
My name is Annie Leal,

13:31.778 --> 13:33.813
and I am from Monterrey, Mexico,

13:33.813 --> 13:36.249
and today I am seeking $300,000

13:36.249 --> 13:39.819
in exchange for a 5%
equity stake in my company,

13:39.819 --> 13:40.953
I Love Chamoy.

13:40.953 --> 13:43.256
Sharks, when I think of
Halloween candy,

13:43.256 --> 13:46.926
I don't think of chocolates,
caramels, or licorice.

13:46.926 --> 13:50.163
No, that's boring.
I think of Mexican candy.

13:50.163 --> 13:53.166
And it's not just me.
Consumers of all backgrounds

13:53.166 --> 13:56.903
can't get enough of its sweet,
spicy, and tangy flavors,

13:56.903 --> 13:59.205
and no other product
encompasses the flavors

13:59.205 --> 14:02.675
and versatility
of Mexican candy like Chamoy.

14:02.675 --> 14:05.678
[ Plays up-tempo song ]

14:05.678 --> 14:06.312
[ Chuckles ]

14:06.312 --> 14:08.948
Chamoy is a traditional
Mexican candy sauce

14:08.948 --> 14:11.084
that is enjoyed over fruits,
vegetables,

14:11.084 --> 14:14.754
drinks, popcorns, chips,
and even by itself.

14:14.754 --> 14:17.724
I Love Chamoy is sugar-free...

14:17.724 --> 14:19.826
carb-free...

14:19.826 --> 14:22.829
and calorie-free.

14:22.829 --> 14:24.163
Soon after we moved to America,

14:24.163 --> 14:26.132
my dad was diagnosed
with diabetes

14:26.132 --> 14:30.036
and could no longer enjoy the
sugary staple we grew up loving.

14:30.036 --> 14:31.304
Seeing him struggle
to find something

14:31.304 --> 14:34.273
that reminded him of home
that he could still enjoy

14:34.273 --> 14:37.009
inspired me to create
what was missing in the market.

14:37.009 --> 14:39.212
I Love Chamoy
is a love letter to my dad,

14:39.212 --> 14:41.214
my culture, and my community.

14:41.214 --> 14:44.183
So, Sharks, who wants to join
I Love Chamoy

14:44.183 --> 14:47.120
and make Mexican candy
accessible to all?

14:47.120 --> 14:49.055
Sharks, give it up
to my wonderful mariachi.

14:49.055 --> 14:50.790
-Whoo! Whoo!
-Wonderful.

14:50.790 --> 14:53.092
-Whoo-hoo!
-Thank you, guys.

14:53.092 --> 14:57.930
[ Playing mariachi
"Shark Tank" music ]

14:57.930 --> 15:00.199
Sounds good.

15:00.199 --> 15:01.834
So, Sharks, in front of you,

15:01.834 --> 15:03.903
you have three
of the most popular ways

15:03.903 --> 15:06.172
that our customers
love to eat I Love Chamoy.

15:06.172 --> 15:08.207
You have a fruta cup and chamoy.

15:08.207 --> 15:11.210
You also have a mangonada,
which is a nondairy

15:11.210 --> 15:13.813
ice cream smoothie
with mango, lime,

15:13.813 --> 15:15.181
and, of course, I Love Chamoy.

15:15.181 --> 15:18.050
And then you have a margarita
rimmed with I Love Chamoy.

15:18.050 --> 15:20.253
So these are sweetened
by monk fruit?

15:20.253 --> 15:22.054
Correct. It's sweetened
with pure monk fruit.

15:22.054 --> 15:24.257
It's an all-natural sweetener,
sugar-free,

15:24.257 --> 15:26.159
carb-free, and calorie-free.

15:26.159 --> 15:27.827
And it complements the Chamoy
quite well.

15:27.827 --> 15:29.262
-Excellent.
-Interesting.

15:29.262 --> 15:31.430
And sugar-free products
are really popular...
Ooh, that is good.

15:31.430 --> 15:34.834
...but when it came
to the Mexican candy category,

15:34.834 --> 15:35.902
there was nothing like this.

15:35.902 --> 15:37.069
So why are you
calling it a candy?

15:37.069 --> 15:39.238
It's really a condiment
or a sauce.

15:39.238 --> 15:41.908
I grew up with it
being a Mexican candy sauce.

15:41.908 --> 15:44.043
We also have
an additional product line

15:44.043 --> 15:46.078
that I haven't showed
you guys yet.

15:46.078 --> 15:47.914
And in order to show you that,
I'm gonna need

15:47.914 --> 15:50.082
the help of Mr. Jason.

15:50.082 --> 15:51.217
Can I borrow you
for a little bit?

15:51.217 --> 15:53.019
-Go ahead, Mr. Jason.
-Beautiful.

15:53.019 --> 15:54.153
So you're gonna
stand right here.

15:54.153 --> 15:56.956
Okay.
So, guys,
in Mexican culture,

15:56.956 --> 15:58.491
the way we like
to break piñatas

15:58.491 --> 16:01.227
is we usually fill them
with something really special,

16:01.227 --> 16:03.162
and then you can
go to town with --
Okay. Great.

16:03.162 --> 16:06.866
Okay. So I'm gonna get
your weapon of choice.

16:06.866 --> 16:08.234
Go with the baseball bat.

16:08.234 --> 16:10.069
Sharks, usually when
we break piñatas,

16:10.069 --> 16:12.271
we count from one to five
in Spanish.

16:12.271 --> 16:13.940
Do you guys want to
help me out?

16:13.940 --> 16:14.941
-Okay.
-Yeah.

16:14.941 --> 16:16.742
All: Uno!

16:16.742 --> 16:18.778
Oh!
Dos! Dos!

16:18.778 --> 16:21.080
All: Dos!

16:21.080 --> 16:23.249
Tres!

16:23.249 --> 16:25.051
-There we go!
-Whoo!

16:25.051 --> 16:26.986
-You took some candy.
-It's open.

16:26.986 --> 16:28.354
Didn't that feel good?

16:28.354 --> 16:30.056
I mean, this is part
of the celebration.

16:30.056 --> 16:32.291
There we go!
What a mess.

16:32.291 --> 16:34.327
-This is our new candy category.
-Oh!

16:34.327 --> 16:36.929
So it's Mexican candy,
but it's sugar-free

16:36.929 --> 16:38.531
chili-watermelon flavor.

16:38.531 --> 16:41.500
This is a new product line
that we soft-launched

16:41.500 --> 16:44.036
a few months ago,
and it was a great success.

16:44.036 --> 16:46.072
-Chamoy gummies?
-Chamoy gummies.

16:46.072 --> 16:47.373
-Let me try one. Ready?
-Absolutely.

16:47.373 --> 16:49.842
It's spicy, it's sweet,
it's tangy.

16:49.842 --> 16:51.277
Ay, Chihuahua, caramba!

16:51.277 --> 16:52.512
-There we go.
-Mmm!

16:52.512 --> 16:55.314
-Oh, it's got a kick to it.
-And where were you selling it?

16:55.314 --> 16:57.116
We're selling it
direct to consumer

16:57.116 --> 16:59.151
completely through our website.

16:59.151 --> 17:00.920
And in our first full year
in business,

17:00.920 --> 17:02.355
which was last year, 2022,

17:02.355 --> 17:05.424
we closed the year
in $550,000 in sales.
Wow.

17:05.424 --> 17:08.294
Year-to-date,
we've done $1.3 million.

17:08.294 --> 17:10.029
-Wow.
-Good for you. Well done.

17:10.029 --> 17:11.130
And we're projected
to close the year

17:11.130 --> 17:12.265
between $3.8 and $4 million.

17:12.265 --> 17:13.432
-Oh, my God!
-Dang!

17:13.432 --> 17:15.167
-Wow. And what is your --
-Wow!

17:15.167 --> 17:17.203
Now, wait, is that the --
That's not even the candy.

17:17.203 --> 17:19.205
You didn't even launch that.
That's just these.

17:19.205 --> 17:21.173
The candy is only $30,000
because we soft-launched it.

17:21.173 --> 17:23.075
It's all coming
from the pink bottle.

17:23.075 --> 17:24.810
How did you build
that customer?

17:24.810 --> 17:25.411
That's a huge jump.

17:25.411 --> 17:27.146
Are you spending a lot
on advertising to do it?

17:27.146 --> 17:30.283
No, we've --
80%, 90% of our sales

17:30.283 --> 17:31.517
are completely organic.

17:31.517 --> 17:35.087
It's been entirely online
through social media.
Really?

17:35.087 --> 17:36.689
And I started posting
about my inspiration,

17:36.689 --> 17:39.458
the fact that I wanted to find
something healthier for my dad

17:39.458 --> 17:41.327
and there wasn't anything
like that available.

17:41.327 --> 17:42.662
How many followers
do you have?

17:42.662 --> 17:45.264
Half a million followers across
different social channels.

17:45.264 --> 17:47.500
We're in around
250 grocery stores in Texas.

17:47.500 --> 17:50.303
We're proudly made in Texas.
We're in H-E-Bs.

17:50.303 --> 17:53.039
We're also
in a nationwide retailer

17:53.039 --> 17:54.440
that specializes
in home goods.

17:54.440 --> 17:56.242
Is it just you, Annie,
or do you have a team?

17:56.242 --> 17:57.610
It's just me.
I talk in "we" a lot.

17:57.610 --> 18:00.112
You're doing
all of this yourself?!
Correct. Yes.

18:00.112 --> 18:01.314
So, Annie, walk us
through the numbers.

18:01.314 --> 18:04.150
How much does it cost to make?
What do you sell it for?
Yes.

18:04.150 --> 18:06.085
What's the wholesale price
to retail?

18:06.085 --> 18:09.088
So we make it
between $1.60 and $2.

18:09.088 --> 18:10.990
And we sell it
direct to consumer

18:10.990 --> 18:12.358
for $12 on our website.

18:12.358 --> 18:15.528
We sell it to retailers
between $3.90 and $4,

18:15.528 --> 18:18.331
and they sell it to their
customers between $6 to $7.

18:18.331 --> 18:20.266
So being direct to consumer,

18:20.266 --> 18:22.335
putting profits
before anything else,

18:22.335 --> 18:25.171
making sure we have cash flow --
all of that has made

18:25.171 --> 18:26.339
such an incredible difference
in my business.

18:26.339 --> 18:28.541
You have no debt right now?
Any debt?
No debt.

18:28.541 --> 18:31.344
Annie, you've got to be making
just a boatload of money.

18:31.344 --> 18:36.148
Our profits for this year
is projected to be 1.5.

18:36.148 --> 18:37.183
-Good for you.
-Thank you.

18:37.183 --> 18:39.318
Are you trying to
get it outside

18:39.318 --> 18:41.420
of the Mexican community?
Absolutely.

18:41.420 --> 18:43.389
So our customer base
is not just exclusive

18:43.389 --> 18:45.324
to Hispanics or Latinos.

18:45.324 --> 18:48.160
I want to have
a bigger footprint in retail.

18:48.160 --> 18:49.462
No matter
how we expand on retail,

18:49.462 --> 18:52.098
I never plan on
dropping the ball

18:52.098 --> 18:53.199
on the social-media aspect.

18:53.199 --> 18:54.300
Corcoran: Annie, I think
you're underestimating

18:54.300 --> 18:57.136
your insurmountable charm
and salesmanship

18:57.136 --> 18:58.371
that you're doing
on social media.

18:58.371 --> 19:00.439
None of that applies
to retail.

19:00.439 --> 19:03.109
So if you're in
for the retail ride,

19:03.109 --> 19:05.177
I'm not with you,
so I'm out.

19:05.177 --> 19:06.345
Thank you, Barbara.

19:06.345 --> 19:07.480
O'Leary: Well, listen,
I've heard enough, Annie.

19:07.480 --> 19:09.148
I'm gonna
make you an offer.

19:09.148 --> 19:12.351
I'll give you the $300,000
for 15%.

19:12.351 --> 19:14.420
Thank you so much
for your offer.

19:14.420 --> 19:17.189
Annie, I don't want to take
a chunk of your business.

19:17.189 --> 19:18.591
I think you can do this.

19:18.591 --> 19:21.327
I'll be a consumer
but not a partner.

19:21.327 --> 19:22.361
-Thank you so much, Lori.
-I'm out.

19:22.361 --> 19:23.629
Really appreciate it.

19:23.629 --> 19:26.232
Well, I too --
I'm a fan of your product.

19:26.232 --> 19:30.169
But what I am
particularly impressed by

19:30.169 --> 19:32.505
is your way to talk
about your business.

19:32.505 --> 19:34.440
You're really
doing everything right.

19:34.440 --> 19:36.442
I would only be money
to you.

19:36.442 --> 19:39.378
This is so far afield
from anything

19:39.378 --> 19:40.546
I really have
any experience in,

19:40.546 --> 19:42.648
so I couldn't lend
that much expertise to you.

19:42.648 --> 19:47.286
So I'm out, but I hope you make
a deal with another Shark.

19:47.286 --> 19:48.387
Thank you so much.

19:48.387 --> 19:50.423
Annie, you've earned
that spot right there.

19:50.423 --> 19:52.224
I mean, you're doing
everything right.

19:52.224 --> 19:54.326
You've gone to social.
You didn't just do it

19:54.326 --> 19:56.595
like a traditional
consumer food product.

19:56.595 --> 20:00.466
Everything's perfect,
except it's not my taste.

20:00.466 --> 20:03.369
I just couldn't be out there
saying it's a great product,

20:03.369 --> 20:05.337
but it's not great for me.

20:05.337 --> 20:07.873
So, unfortunately,
for those reasons, I'm out.

20:09.442 --> 20:11.177
Well, all Sharks are out,

20:11.177 --> 20:14.080
and all chamoy leads
to Mr. Wonderful.

20:14.080 --> 20:16.315
[ Thunder rumbles ]

20:16.315 --> 20:18.951
What do you want to do,
Annie?

20:18.951 --> 20:24.857
♪♪

20:28.561 --> 20:30.529
Narrator:
Four Sharks are out.

20:30.529 --> 20:35.334
Kevin has offered Annie $300,000
for a 15% stake

20:35.334 --> 20:37.670
in her sweet-and-spicy
sauce and candy business,

20:37.670 --> 20:41.340
I Love Chamoy,
but it's a much bigger stake

20:41.340 --> 20:44.176
than the 5%
she came in offering.

20:44.176 --> 20:45.411
Well, all Sharks are out

20:45.411 --> 20:49.048
and all chamoy leads
to Mr. Wonderful.

20:51.517 --> 20:55.454
What do you want to do,
Annie?

20:55.454 --> 20:59.125
Mr. Wonderful,
would you consider doing

20:59.125 --> 21:03.229
$350,000 for 7%?

21:03.229 --> 21:06.298
No.
Here's my concerns.

21:06.298 --> 21:07.500
I think retail is harder
than you think.

21:07.500 --> 21:09.368
You've heard that already
from the Sharks.

21:09.368 --> 21:11.437
We've all been through
the retail meat grinder.

21:11.437 --> 21:13.639
I'm a big believer
in what you've done on social.

21:13.639 --> 21:16.275
But then there's the factor
that I was worried about.

21:16.275 --> 21:18.477
And, you know,
it's Halloween here,

21:18.477 --> 21:20.513
and there's tombstones
and skulls.

21:20.513 --> 21:21.780
Are you getting creepy?

21:21.780 --> 21:25.384
No, I'm thinking you get
run over by a truck. The risk.

21:25.384 --> 21:27.386
Well, I was gonna say --
And you're gonna walk in

21:27.386 --> 21:28.721
and just operate
the company, right?

21:28.721 --> 21:30.589
-You know what? I mean...
-You're the whole deal.

21:30.589 --> 21:31.790
...that is not
a legitimate reason.

21:31.790 --> 21:34.527
We've built a really,
really strong brand.

21:34.527 --> 21:36.395
And I just want to say,
when it comes to moving

21:36.395 --> 21:37.563
into retail and taking --

21:37.563 --> 21:40.533
I'm a big fan
of taking calculated risks.

21:40.533 --> 21:41.634
Obviously, and it shows.

21:41.634 --> 21:42.768
I don't necessarily agree
about getting --

21:42.768 --> 21:44.570
if you get hit by a truck,
those are other problems.

21:44.570 --> 21:49.241
But you do have the money to
hire another business partner,

21:49.241 --> 21:50.576
which I would definitely,

21:50.576 --> 21:51.777
whether you make a deal
or not...

21:51.777 --> 21:53.679
You countered, and you're
allowed to say no, Annie.

21:53.679 --> 21:56.081
Honestly, Annie,
what if he got hit by a truck?

21:56.081 --> 21:56.749
That's right, Kevin.

21:56.749 --> 21:58.717
-Then I would take his chair.
-I look at it this way.

21:58.717 --> 22:00.653
I have a whole team of people
that work with me,

22:00.653 --> 22:02.822
and they have for decades.
They're Team Wonderful.

22:02.822 --> 22:05.558
Everybody knows that.
And you'll meet them.

22:05.558 --> 22:07.626
But, you know, there's enough
risk in this deal

22:07.626 --> 22:11.463
because the big guys in this
space can easily knock you off.

22:11.463 --> 22:12.665
And then all you've got

22:12.665 --> 22:14.834
is whatever the brand is
at that point,

22:14.834 --> 22:18.204
'cause they can fight on price,
they can fight on distribution.

22:18.204 --> 22:19.438
I get all that.

22:19.438 --> 22:20.773
I've made you an offer
I'm comfortable with.

22:20.773 --> 22:23.609
You're not dead to me right now.
You could be in a minute.

22:23.609 --> 22:26.245
Stick to your guns, Annie.
Stick to your guns.

22:26.245 --> 22:28.380
15% is too much.
I've been --

22:28.380 --> 22:29.548
I'm gonna stick
with my guns, too, Annie.

22:29.548 --> 22:32.484
I'll do the deal.
I'll give you $300,000 for 15%,

22:32.484 --> 22:33.552
and you've got a partner,

22:33.552 --> 22:36.422
and we ride
into the mariachi sunset.

22:36.422 --> 22:37.489
You're brutal.

22:37.489 --> 22:38.757
I'm not brutal.
I'm Mr. Wonderful.

22:38.757 --> 22:40.759
I came here to make a deal,
but this is breaking my heart.

22:40.759 --> 22:43.896
I'm not competing with anybody,
just myself.

22:43.896 --> 22:46.532
And I'll tell you this --
I came here to get a deal,

22:46.532 --> 22:48.934
to make my parents proud,
to make my community proud.

22:48.934 --> 22:51.470
And because
I truly believe...
You already have.

22:51.470 --> 22:52.538
...in how far this --
thank you --

22:52.538 --> 22:56.375
how far this company can go,

22:56.375 --> 22:59.278
would you consider doing
$300,000 for 8%,

22:59.278 --> 23:00.646
and we have a deal?

23:00.646 --> 23:01.847
Well, I haven't
been flexible yet,

23:01.847 --> 23:04.383
but I'll go to 12 1/2
and I'll do it there.

23:04.383 --> 23:05.551
That's my final offer.

23:05.551 --> 23:07.453
12 is so high.
In the spirit of Halloween --

23:07.453 --> 23:09.555
-It's not so high.
-In the spirit of Halloween.

23:09.555 --> 23:11.490
I've been working really hard
to make all of these sales...

23:11.490 --> 23:13.325
Annie, you're
insanely profitable.

23:13.325 --> 23:14.627
That's the difference.
Thank you.

23:14.627 --> 23:16.462
If you were losing money,

23:16.462 --> 23:18.497
then the 3%, 5%
doesn't really matter.

23:18.497 --> 23:20.799
Meet in the middle, guys.
It's a great deal.

23:20.799 --> 23:21.867
O'Leary:
All of this is interesting,

23:21.867 --> 23:23.636
but none of them
are making you an offer.

23:23.636 --> 23:25.738
I'm the only Shark
that really believes in you

23:25.738 --> 23:28.374
with his money.
I'll do it at 12.5%.

23:28.374 --> 23:30.376
My final offer, Annie.

23:33.545 --> 23:35.581
-I can't take the 12.5%.
-I appreciate it.

23:35.581 --> 23:37.683
Yay!
Good for you.

23:37.683 --> 23:39.652
-Thank you so much. Bye, guys.
-Great job, Annie.

23:39.652 --> 23:42.454
Greiner: Good job, Annie.
Congratulations.

23:43.622 --> 23:45.724
Leal: That was a blood-sucking
offer that Kevin made.

23:45.724 --> 23:48.761
His ask, 12.5%,
was just way too high.

23:48.761 --> 23:50.696
I've worked really hard for
I Love Chamoy.

23:50.696 --> 23:51.864
We're profitable.

23:51.864 --> 23:54.533
We have so many new things
coming out, and it's just --

23:54.533 --> 23:56.669
I wasn't able to
meet him at that number.

23:56.669 --> 23:58.604
Narrator: For our milestone
15th season,

23:58.604 --> 24:01.407
we're counting down the top 15
Shark Tank companies

24:01.407 --> 24:03.676
with the highest total
retail sales.

24:03.676 --> 24:08.514
Number 3 is Scrub Daddy
with $926 million.

24:08.514 --> 24:13.352
Number 2 is Everlywell
with a whopping $1.1 billion.

24:13.352 --> 24:15.621
And the top spot goes to Bombas

24:15.621 --> 24:19.491
with $1.3 billion
in retail sales.

24:28.634 --> 24:35.774
♪♪

24:35.774 --> 24:37.743
Narrator:
Next up are two artists

24:37.743 --> 24:39.611
with a passion for pumpkins.

24:39.611 --> 24:46.785
♪♪

24:46.785 --> 24:49.288
[ Thunder rumbles ]

24:51.557 --> 24:53.692
Hey Sharks.
I'm Marc Evan.

24:53.692 --> 24:54.760
And I'm Chris Soria.

24:54.760 --> 24:56.729
We're from New York,
and we're the co-founders

24:56.729 --> 24:58.597
of a crazy carving company.

24:58.597 --> 25:00.232
We are...

25:03.369 --> 25:03.869
[ Laughter ]

25:03.869 --> 25:06.505
Together:
...Maniac Pumpkin Carvers.

25:06.505 --> 25:08.674
We're lifelong artists,
Halloween lovers,

25:08.674 --> 25:11.577
and professional carvers
who have been honing our skills

25:11.577 --> 25:13.579
and techniques for decades.

25:13.579 --> 25:15.581
We produce custom pieces
that have been featured

25:15.581 --> 25:17.816
and displayed
in prestigious museums,

25:17.816 --> 25:20.753
events, and installations
across the country.

25:20.753 --> 25:22.688
From detailed portraits

25:22.688 --> 25:24.790
to re-creations
of famous works of art

25:24.790 --> 25:26.058
and iconic insignia.

25:26.058 --> 25:29.762
We've carved out our niche,
elevating this nostalgic pastime

25:29.762 --> 25:31.030
to an ephemeral art form.

25:31.030 --> 25:34.633
And now we're here to help
all of you with our...

25:34.633 --> 25:36.502
Together:
...School of Pumpkin.

25:36.502 --> 25:37.936
We'll feature online
carving classes,

25:37.936 --> 25:40.539
teaching a wide variety
of pumpkin techniques

25:40.539 --> 25:43.709
to help unlock
your true pumpkin potential.

25:43.709 --> 25:45.744
And we'll offer
all the tools and resources

25:45.744 --> 25:47.980
one needs to carve
the perfect pumpkin.

25:47.980 --> 25:50.783
Our School of Pumpkin
is still growing on the vine.

25:50.783 --> 25:55.654
That's why we're seeking
$150,000 for 8% equity

25:55.654 --> 25:56.955
to really help it thrive.

25:56.955 --> 26:00.659
So, Sharks, who wants to
get pumped up with us and...

26:00.659 --> 26:02.094
Together:
...pumpkin like a pro?

26:02.094 --> 26:06.565
So how would you guys release
my pumpkin-carving potential?

26:06.565 --> 26:08.667
Well, we've been
teaching art

26:08.667 --> 26:11.570
for over a decade
in various forms.

26:11.570 --> 26:13.906
Our courses will get you
through the steps

26:13.906 --> 26:16.008
to carve something that
you're really proud of.

26:16.008 --> 26:18.811
And even if your first one
is not a masterpiece,

26:18.811 --> 26:20.112
we're still gonna help you
get away

26:20.112 --> 26:23.515
from the classic jack-o'-lantern
that you've done in the past

26:23.515 --> 26:24.650
and do something really fun.

26:24.650 --> 26:27.186
Tell us about the business.
What are we buying into?

26:27.186 --> 26:30.756
And what is the tangible thing
that the consumer is buying?

26:30.756 --> 26:32.024
The last three years

26:32.024 --> 26:35.027
were a real game-changer
in our business,

26:35.027 --> 26:39.631
which a lot of it depended on
live, in-person events.

26:39.631 --> 26:40.799
And with the pandemic,

26:40.799 --> 26:43.936
we immediately transitioned
to doing online classes,

26:43.936 --> 26:46.438
online events
and demonstrations.

26:46.438 --> 26:47.539
Are you making any money?

26:47.539 --> 26:48.841
In the last three years,

26:48.841 --> 26:53.812
we sold over $170,000 worth
of virtual-class experiences...

26:53.812 --> 26:54.847
-Wow.
-Good for you.

26:54.847 --> 26:56.982
...and $90,000 of tool kits.

26:56.982 --> 26:59.785
So you do have a tool kit.
We just don't see it.

26:59.785 --> 27:02.921
Our tool kits currently
are hand-selected items

27:02.921 --> 27:06.859
that we've been using
that we love and recommend.

27:06.859 --> 27:08.093
But we do have dreams

27:08.093 --> 27:10.863
of releasing
our own proprietary tools.

27:10.863 --> 27:12.965
Just in the last year,
how much did you make?

27:12.965 --> 27:16.034
Last year our gross sales
were $294,000.

27:16.034 --> 27:17.903
But that's for pumpkins,
not classes.

27:17.903 --> 27:20.706
No, our business, we do all
different types of things

27:20.706 --> 27:22.708
pumpkin-related,
including events,

27:22.708 --> 27:25.944
classes, demonstrations,
and custom carving orders.

27:25.944 --> 27:28.947
If I want to order
Mr. Wonderful pumpkin,

27:28.947 --> 27:30.716
do I send you a picture?
And he will.

27:30.716 --> 27:32.017
For sure he will.

27:32.017 --> 27:33.819
How do I get
my face in 3D?

27:33.819 --> 27:35.821
Are you using laser cutters?
How are you doing this?

27:35.821 --> 27:37.890
We do all the artwork
by hand.

27:37.890 --> 27:39.124
And that's real pumpkin?

27:39.124 --> 27:41.760
These are real pumpkins
carved by hand.

27:41.760 --> 27:42.995
We're lifelong artists.

27:42.995 --> 27:47.032
People hire us to do portraits
and logos and movie posters,

27:47.032 --> 27:48.867
all kinds
of amazing designs.

27:48.867 --> 27:50.769
So somebody watching
on television --

27:50.769 --> 27:54.039
can they go to a website
and upload a picture,

27:54.039 --> 27:56.842
and you'll send them a pumpkin?
Or does it have to be local?

27:56.842 --> 27:59.044
We do ship pumpkins
all over the country.

27:59.044 --> 28:02.614
The cost of shipping a live
pumpkin is a little prohibitive.

28:02.614 --> 28:03.882
Nothing would
make me happier

28:03.882 --> 28:06.084
than sending a picture
of Mr. Wonderful....

28:06.084 --> 28:09.021
Yeah!
...and you sending me
a carved 3D pumpkin

28:09.021 --> 28:12.824
of Mr. Wonderful so I can
smash it on Halloween night.

28:12.824 --> 28:14.927
Or it could have a spike
in its head, like, yeah.

28:14.927 --> 28:16.061
-Even better. See?
-Even better.

28:16.061 --> 28:18.096
I think we should offer
a Wonder special.

28:18.096 --> 28:20.933
And I'll get a 7% royalty.
What would that cost?

28:20.933 --> 28:23.735
So a portrait of Mr. Wonderful
would probably be

28:23.735 --> 28:26.738
somewhere in
the $600 to $800 range.

28:26.738 --> 28:27.739
Oh, so worth it.

28:27.739 --> 28:28.974
You have to do the work
yourself,

28:28.974 --> 28:31.009
or do you have a lot of carvers
working for you?

28:31.009 --> 28:33.812
We do.
We have a team of artists

28:33.812 --> 28:38.183
that we staff mostly for
the peak weeks of October.

28:38.183 --> 28:40.719
The rest of the time,
we're cranking out

28:40.719 --> 28:41.853
as much of it as we can.

28:41.853 --> 28:43.155
But you're all pumpkin
all the time now,

28:43.155 --> 28:44.890
'cause it sounds to me
like you're pulling out

28:44.890 --> 28:49.161
between $150,000 and $200,000
each a year as pumpkin dudes.

28:49.161 --> 28:52.064
No, they're all pumpkin
all the time one month a year.

28:52.064 --> 28:54.766
Well, except I'm thinking
maybe I want to do a little

28:54.766 --> 28:56.768
pumpkin action off season.
Can I do that?

28:56.768 --> 28:58.103
When we first started
the business,

28:58.103 --> 29:01.206
our season was really the week
or two before Halloween.

29:01.206 --> 29:03.809
Now our season
is a quarter of the year.

29:03.809 --> 29:06.044
So in August and September,

29:06.044 --> 29:08.246
we're carving tons of things
that are gonna be used

29:08.246 --> 29:10.916
in product placements
and advertisements.
Ah.

29:10.916 --> 29:12.150
It's really
content creation.

29:12.150 --> 29:14.653
Could you carve my face
on a watermelon?

29:14.653 --> 29:15.220
-Absolutely.
-Absolutely.

29:15.220 --> 29:17.689
Could you put Mark Cuban's
on the grape?

29:17.689 --> 29:19.825
Guys!
[ Laughter ]

29:19.825 --> 29:21.093
I have a more kind of

29:21.093 --> 29:22.961
philosophical question
for you guys.

29:22.961 --> 29:24.696
You have
this great thing going.

29:24.696 --> 29:26.698
It's small.
It's seasonal.

29:26.698 --> 29:28.967
It seems tricky to scale,

29:28.967 --> 29:30.736
and you have
a great thing going.

29:30.736 --> 29:32.004
So why are you here?

29:32.004 --> 29:34.973
We really want to get into
the direct-consumer market.

29:34.973 --> 29:37.876
Halloween is
a $10-billion-a-year industry.

29:37.876 --> 29:38.977
-Yeah, baby!
-Yes, it is.

29:38.977 --> 29:40.946
149 million people
are expected

29:40.946 --> 29:43.015
to carve pumpkins
this year.

29:43.015 --> 29:46.018
We want all of those people
to be using our tools

29:46.018 --> 29:48.286
and downloading
our streaming classes.

29:48.286 --> 29:50.322
-But you don't have tools.
-You don't have the tools, yeah.

29:50.322 --> 29:52.858
You gotta have tools
with your name on.
Yeah.

29:52.858 --> 29:55.827
You got to have
Maniac Pumpkin Carvers knives.

29:55.827 --> 29:56.962
Knives!

29:56.962 --> 29:59.865
How quickly are your
online classes growing now?

29:59.865 --> 30:01.900
So far we haven't been

30:01.900 --> 30:03.669
offering them
direct to consumer.

30:03.669 --> 30:05.003
Oh, small detail.

30:05.003 --> 30:06.805
Oh, you don't have
classes to people?
Who are you selling them to?

30:06.805 --> 30:07.939
To corporate clients.

30:07.939 --> 30:11.943
They have us do a live
Zoom class or webinar.

30:11.943 --> 30:14.880
It's a great, fun
team-building exercise.

30:14.880 --> 30:15.881
Yeah, but you know what?

30:15.881 --> 30:16.982
You're barking up
the wrong tree.

30:16.982 --> 30:19.951
Why not apply your skills
to another market?

30:19.951 --> 30:21.953
Do you ever do
sand castles?

30:21.953 --> 30:24.189
That's temporary.
It takes artistic talent.

30:24.189 --> 30:27.793
Why curtail your whole business
into four months a year?

30:27.793 --> 30:28.994
I don't see
the potential in it.

30:28.994 --> 30:31.063
So for that reason,
I'm out.

30:31.063 --> 30:33.265
Okay. Thank you.
I think you guys have done
a fantastic job

30:33.265 --> 30:35.334
articulating a market
I'd never heard of.

30:35.334 --> 30:38.003
But, guys, I don't see
a scalable business here.

30:38.003 --> 30:40.872
Your deal itself is
very, very scary.

30:40.872 --> 30:42.340
So I'm out.

30:42.340 --> 30:44.976
Look, guys, you're looking
for a way to scale.

30:44.976 --> 30:48.013
That's the hard part, right?
I just don't know that

30:48.013 --> 30:50.082
online pumpkin-carving classes
will be huge.

30:50.082 --> 30:51.917
That makes it
a tough investment.

30:51.917 --> 30:53.318
So for those reasons,
I'm out.

30:53.318 --> 30:54.953
But congrats on what
you've accomplished.

30:54.953 --> 30:56.054
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

30:56.054 --> 30:58.290
Listen, there's a lot
of pumpkin-carving tools

30:58.290 --> 31:01.293
out there, actually,
and there's diagrams

31:01.293 --> 31:04.029
and stencils
and things like that.

31:04.029 --> 31:05.897
I don't think trying to compete
with what else

31:05.897 --> 31:08.166
is out there already
really makes any sense.

31:08.166 --> 31:10.936
So I'm not gonna
take the journey, I'm sorry.

31:10.936 --> 31:12.971
I wish you good luck,
but I'm out.

31:12.971 --> 31:14.172
Thank you.

31:14.172 --> 31:18.777
Guys, my business today
is really managing the line

31:18.777 --> 31:20.345
between art and commerce,

31:20.345 --> 31:23.215
taking artists who make movies
and TV shows

31:23.215 --> 31:26.985
and making those movies
and television shows profitable.

31:26.985 --> 31:30.322
And what I see today
is two terrific artists

31:30.322 --> 31:34.226
with a fabulous
seasonal activity,

31:34.226 --> 31:37.028
which is fun for you guys to do.

31:37.028 --> 31:38.230
And I actually think

31:38.230 --> 31:41.066
if you had more business
running through your veins --

31:41.066 --> 31:42.901
you'd be selling images
and everything else --

31:42.901 --> 31:44.269
I think if you
actually did that,

31:44.269 --> 31:46.104
you would be
very, very unhappy.

31:46.104 --> 31:49.875
And an unhappy entrepreneur is
not a successful entrepreneur.

31:49.875 --> 31:51.843
So for that reason, I'm out.

31:53.378 --> 31:55.447
-Have fun, guys. Congrats.
-Get ready for those orders.

31:55.447 --> 31:57.949
-Thank you for sharing with us.
-Thank you very much.

31:57.949 --> 31:59.217
Cuban:
Congrats, guys.

31:59.217 --> 32:02.120
Evan: We are disappointed that
we didn't get an investment,

32:02.120 --> 32:04.189
but it's not gonna stop us
from doing what we do.

32:04.189 --> 32:05.323
We're just gonna
keep moving forward,

32:05.323 --> 32:08.927
making pumpkin art,
teaching pumpkin classes.

32:08.927 --> 32:10.495
It's October.
This is our busy season.

32:10.495 --> 32:13.298
We have to get back
to the studio and get carving.

32:13.298 --> 32:15.934
It's gonna be a crazy season
no matter what.

32:15.934 --> 32:18.937
♪♪

32:25.143 --> 32:27.913
Narrator: Next into the Tank
is a way to experience

32:27.913 --> 32:30.048
some of life's dark mysteries.

32:30.048 --> 32:31.817
[ Snarls ]

32:31.817 --> 32:36.955
♪♪

32:36.955 --> 32:38.990
[ Thunder rumbles ]

32:40.325 --> 32:43.061
Hi, Sharks.
My name is Mike Huberty.

32:43.061 --> 32:44.329
And I'm Allison Jornlin.

32:44.329 --> 32:49.768
And we're asking for $250,000
for 15% of our company.

32:49.768 --> 32:51.336
Can ghosts make you rich?

32:51.336 --> 32:55.207
September 24th, 1869 --
the first Black Friday.

32:55.207 --> 32:57.108
The price of gold
collapses.

32:57.108 --> 32:59.244
The United States stock market
is devastated.

32:59.244 --> 33:03.815
Except for one tycoon
who anticipated the disaster

33:03.815 --> 33:05.183
and came out on top.

33:05.183 --> 33:07.185
Cornelius Vanderbilt.

33:07.185 --> 33:09.254
Because he had a secret.

33:09.254 --> 33:11.122
He was living with
a psychic medium

33:11.122 --> 33:12.991
who would hold séances
in his house

33:12.991 --> 33:15.093
and ask the spirits
what the future

33:15.093 --> 33:16.528
of the stock market
might hold.

33:16.528 --> 33:19.965
When asked how other business
leaders could experience

33:19.965 --> 33:22.801
similar success,
Vanderbilt said...

33:22.801 --> 33:23.902
"Do as I do..."

33:23.902 --> 33:25.904
[ Evil laughter ]

33:25.904 --> 33:28.039
"...consult the spirits."

33:28.039 --> 33:31.042
Sharks, it's real
haunted history like this

33:31.042 --> 33:33.144
that inspired
my sister and I to found

33:33.144 --> 33:35.013
American Ghost Walks --

33:35.013 --> 33:37.249
deeply researched
history tours

33:37.249 --> 33:40.352
of beautiful locations
with haunted pasts.

33:40.352 --> 33:43.889
Our tours are
entertaining presentations

33:43.889 --> 33:45.423
of remarkable facts

33:45.423 --> 33:50.262
so that even nonbelievers
have a wickedly good time.

33:50.262 --> 33:53.365
So, Sharks,
Cornelius Vanderbilt knew

33:53.365 --> 33:55.500
that ghosts could
make you rich.

33:55.500 --> 33:59.571
So who's ready to
consult the spirits

33:59.571 --> 34:03.975
and join American Ghost Walks
for some real ghost stories

34:03.975 --> 34:06.278
and real spooky fun?

34:06.278 --> 34:09.014
What is your business?
It's tours or it's virtual?

34:09.014 --> 34:12.250
It's live, guided
haunted history tours.

34:12.250 --> 34:15.253
Now we're in seven states
and Puerto Rico.

34:15.253 --> 34:17.255
Good for you.
How many people
do you have giving the tours?

34:17.255 --> 34:19.124
We have about 32 employees.

34:19.124 --> 34:21.026
-Wow.
-I thought you guys were a joke.

34:21.026 --> 34:22.227
You have a real business here.

34:22.227 --> 34:24.262
Are the tour guides --
are they playing a part,

34:24.262 --> 34:26.564
or are they just very neutral
and explaining a story?

34:26.564 --> 34:29.334
Great question.
The tour guides are people

34:29.334 --> 34:31.303
who are engaged
and love the paranormal.

34:31.303 --> 34:33.171
Blum: Almost every horror movie
that we make,

34:33.171 --> 34:35.140
there has to be one authority.

34:35.140 --> 34:38.043
The audience, at least,
has to believe

34:38.043 --> 34:39.344
that this person
is an authority

34:39.344 --> 34:41.212
and really believes
in the paranormal.

34:41.212 --> 34:43.214
So the casting
of your tour guides

34:43.214 --> 34:45.216
is extraordinarily important,
I would imagine.

34:45.216 --> 34:47.519
Absolutely.
Which is why
we hire people

34:47.519 --> 34:49.387
who have a passion
for this already.

34:49.387 --> 34:51.256
It's people who already
had an interest

34:51.256 --> 34:53.258
in true crime
and ghost stories,

34:53.258 --> 34:56.227
and they were doing this
already for fun

34:56.227 --> 34:57.362
and taking
their friends around.

34:57.362 --> 34:59.331
But we write a script,

34:59.331 --> 35:01.333
do the research,
find the stories.

35:01.333 --> 35:04.069
Like, in Los Angeles
and Chicago, it's easy.

35:04.069 --> 35:05.270
There's a ton
of public spaces.

35:05.270 --> 35:07.172
You've got buildings that have
been around for 100 years

35:07.172 --> 35:09.074
that have history,
that have ghost stories.

35:09.074 --> 35:10.108
You go right
in front of them.

35:10.108 --> 35:12.277
Some of the smaller towns
are exciting

35:12.277 --> 35:15.447
because you're finding stories
that nobody else has.

35:15.447 --> 35:17.415
How long has the business
been going on

35:17.415 --> 35:18.516
and how much are you making?

35:18.516 --> 35:21.186
Allison started in 2008
in Milwaukee,

35:21.186 --> 35:22.687
and then I started
in Madison in 2010.

35:22.687 --> 35:25.357
Started a tour in Minneapolis.
The next year was Saint Paul.

35:25.357 --> 35:27.092
Next year was
a vacation town.

35:27.092 --> 35:29.194
Were they all
equally successful?

35:29.194 --> 35:31.429
No.
[ Laughter ]

35:31.429 --> 35:32.764
All these are cities
in the north.

35:32.764 --> 35:34.532
What do you do
in the winter?
"No." "No."

35:34.532 --> 35:36.568
Well, in the winter time,
a lot of them close down.

35:36.568 --> 35:40.905
But so in 2020, Minnesota and
Wisconsin are our only states.

35:40.905 --> 35:42.273
So we made $92,000.

35:42.273 --> 35:44.542
Made as means profit or grossed,
when you say 92,000?

35:44.542 --> 35:47.278
That is grossed.
You grossed $92,000.

35:47.278 --> 35:50.115
And so then we grossed
in 2021,

35:50.115 --> 35:53.284
when we added Illinois,
$392,000.

35:53.284 --> 35:55.487
-How much did you spend?
-Ooh, that's a lot.

35:55.487 --> 35:57.589
We spent -- let's see,
it was $392,000.

35:57.589 --> 36:00.291
We spent $300,000.
Wow. That's a lot.

36:00.291 --> 36:01.459
-So you made $92,000 in profit?
-Correct.

36:01.459 --> 36:04.129
Right. Continue.
What about now?

36:04.129 --> 36:08.033
2022,
we moved to $546,000.

36:08.033 --> 36:10.068
What was the net of 2022?

36:10.068 --> 36:11.536
Net of '22 was negative.

36:11.536 --> 36:13.505
Negative. Okay.
How much did you lose?

36:13.505 --> 36:15.573
-We lost $42,000.
-Got it.

36:15.573 --> 36:17.642
We reinvested
in the business that year.

36:17.642 --> 36:22.547
So that's when we spent money
buying a tour in Chicago.

36:22.547 --> 36:25.250
You bought one that existed?
That's interesting.

36:25.250 --> 36:27.585
Yes, acquisitions are
very important in this business.

36:27.585 --> 36:29.421
How much did you spend
on the acquisitions?

36:29.421 --> 36:31.289
About $115,000.

36:31.289 --> 36:33.425
What's your projected
gross in '23?

36:33.425 --> 36:36.594
We're projecting
about $650,000.

36:36.594 --> 36:40.198
And what's your
projected spend in '23?

36:40.198 --> 36:41.599
$600,000.

36:41.599 --> 36:44.335
Right, so tiny profit.
So right now --

36:44.335 --> 36:45.503
And are you guys
doing this full-time?

36:45.503 --> 36:47.405
Oh, we quit our jobs.
We quit our jobs.

36:47.405 --> 36:49.507
So this is it.
We're full-time
professional weirdos.

36:49.507 --> 36:51.643
How much are you pulling out
of the business right now?

36:51.643 --> 36:54.245
I usually, I budget,
and then when I see the bills,

36:54.245 --> 36:56.448
I pull out enough
to pay the bills.

36:56.448 --> 36:58.383
About how much?
'Cause you're talking about
bringing in an investor.

36:58.383 --> 36:59.517
They gotta pull something
out too, right?

36:59.517 --> 37:01.553
Absolutely.
You got to wet your beak
on a deal.

37:01.553 --> 37:03.254
Well, they're in
a growth stage.

37:03.254 --> 37:04.656
Right, we are definitely --
thank you, Jason,

37:04.656 --> 37:06.524
for for saying that.
You're welcome.

37:06.524 --> 37:08.760
We're in a growth position
right now.

37:08.760 --> 37:11.396
Is that a different way of
saying you can't make any money?

37:11.396 --> 37:12.630
-No, no!
-No.

37:12.630 --> 37:16.134
No, it's saying that we've
invested in acquisitions

37:16.134 --> 37:18.369
and we've made
that money back.

37:18.369 --> 37:21.439
And now we've discovered
a scalable business model

37:21.439 --> 37:25.376
that we want to take nationwide,
but that's not the limit.

37:25.376 --> 37:27.445
I get it. I get the model.
It's a service business.

37:27.445 --> 37:29.714
Right.
But, really, you want
to be profitable.

37:29.714 --> 37:32.450
Well, let's talk about
cruise excursions next,

37:32.450 --> 37:35.353
because we've broken
into the cruise market.

37:35.353 --> 37:36.521
That's where
we're going to see --

37:36.521 --> 37:38.590
-The haunted cruise?
-Yeah.

37:38.590 --> 37:42.260
Guys, I desperately wanted
to have

37:42.260 --> 37:43.695
a successful
production company.

37:43.695 --> 37:46.664
The first movie we ever did,
which was "Paranormal Activity,"

37:46.664 --> 37:49.601
and I thought
after we had that movie,

37:49.601 --> 37:53.705
I'm gonna do low-budget
horror movies and nothing else.

37:53.705 --> 37:57.275
And I was lucky I had that
success when I was 35 years old.

37:57.275 --> 37:59.277
If I was 20, I would have said,

37:59.277 --> 38:01.412
"I want to make the next
'Transformers.'

38:01.412 --> 38:02.480
I want to make a big,
expensive..."

38:02.480 --> 38:04.315
But I said,
"I want to do nothing

38:04.315 --> 38:05.583
but low-budget horror movies."

38:05.583 --> 38:08.286
And that's how
I grew my business

38:08.286 --> 38:09.587
to what it is today.

38:09.587 --> 38:13.925
And what I hear is that
you're spread way too thin.

38:13.925 --> 38:18.530
You guys are not spending
enough time on what you have.

38:18.530 --> 38:20.765
And if I give you
one piece of advice,

38:20.765 --> 38:22.934
is to try and focus
on the assets that you have

38:22.934 --> 38:26.504
and make them more profitable
before you take in outside money

38:26.504 --> 38:28.740
or before you spend more money,
in any case.

38:28.740 --> 38:31.309
And for those reasons,
and I wish you the best of luck,

38:31.309 --> 38:33.344
I'm out.

38:33.344 --> 38:34.779
I think it's fun
what you're doing,

38:34.779 --> 38:38.316
and I think it's great passion
and interest for you.

38:38.316 --> 38:40.685
But I agree with everything
that Jason said.

38:40.685 --> 38:43.454
And for those reasons,
I'm out.

38:43.454 --> 38:46.491
Well, we appreciate
your advice.
Absolutely.

38:46.491 --> 38:47.625
The more I listen to you,

38:47.625 --> 38:49.861
on what your plan is,
the more confused I am.

38:49.861 --> 38:52.897
But it just dawned on me
that I think you're doing

38:52.897 --> 38:56.534
what usually puts most of my
entrepreneurs out of business.

38:56.534 --> 38:57.836
It's falling in love
with the next rainbow

38:57.836 --> 38:59.838
before you finish
the last rainbow.
Yeah.

38:59.838 --> 39:02.674
You really haven't
given us anything concrete

39:02.674 --> 39:05.443
that makes us feel
like your core business

39:05.443 --> 39:08.346
has been profitable,
consistent

39:08.346 --> 39:09.681
before you go on
to something else.

39:09.681 --> 39:13.618
So for that reason,
I'm out, yeah.

39:13.618 --> 39:15.453
Look, guys, you have
to be more concrete,

39:15.453 --> 39:16.487
to Barbara's point.

39:16.487 --> 39:17.722
If you would have
come out here and said,

39:17.722 --> 39:21.459
"We're good at these tours.
We know how to double them.

39:21.459 --> 39:23.695
There's 1,400 of them,

39:23.695 --> 39:25.830
and we want to buy
the top 100" --

39:25.830 --> 39:28.600
if you would have been
very specific in that strategy,

39:28.600 --> 39:30.468
that might have
gotten my interest,

39:30.468 --> 39:32.337
but it was a little bit
all over the map.

39:32.337 --> 39:34.806
So for those reasons,
I'm out.

39:34.806 --> 39:39.310
Okay, 'cause we also have not
broken into merchandise yet.

39:39.310 --> 39:41.412
Number one --
we got a sweet logo.

39:41.412 --> 39:42.780
That logo's gonna look
great on t-shirts.

39:42.780 --> 39:45.683
You are not in the merch!
You are in the tour business!

39:45.683 --> 39:47.652
-It's true.
-You do not listen to my advice!

39:47.652 --> 39:49.387
O'Leary:
I'll tell you the trouble
I'm having with this deal.

39:49.387 --> 39:50.722
I think you asked
for too much money.

39:50.722 --> 39:53.558
I'm so intrigued with it.
It's so unique.

39:53.558 --> 39:56.427
The trouble is, it's $250,000,

39:56.427 --> 39:57.862
a quarter of $1 million.
Yes.

39:57.862 --> 39:59.631
You can't just take a flyer.
So I have to make that back.

39:59.631 --> 40:02.500
Now, my options are
I give you the $250,000,

40:02.500 --> 40:04.569
or I buy another watch,

40:04.569 --> 40:07.639
and most of my watches
appreciate in value.

40:07.639 --> 40:08.873
That's what happens.

40:08.873 --> 40:10.775
And that's the only reason
I work is to buy more watches

40:10.775 --> 40:12.744
and sometimes
give it to guys like you.

40:12.744 --> 40:14.579
But you're riskier
than a new watch.

40:14.579 --> 40:18.449
If this was 50 or a hunski,
maybe.

40:18.449 --> 40:19.584
"A hunski."

40:19.584 --> 40:21.819
And, you know, it's not clear
to me how I 10x on this.

40:21.819 --> 40:23.788
I gotta make
2.5 million bucks.

40:23.788 --> 40:25.523
That's what we do
in Shark Tank.

40:25.523 --> 40:26.591
We want winners.

40:26.591 --> 40:28.426
It's a $500 million
industry, though.

40:28.426 --> 40:29.928
Yeah, yeah,
but we can't get near --

40:29.928 --> 40:33.665
You're nowhere near a place
to spin enough cash

40:33.665 --> 40:38.369
so that every month I get
my $25,000 in distributions.

40:38.369 --> 40:39.470
It's a service business.

40:39.470 --> 40:40.738
We're not gonna
take it public.

40:40.738 --> 40:44.575
It's gotta spin cash
so that I can wet my beak.

40:44.575 --> 40:46.511
You know, I don't want
to ghost the money.

40:46.511 --> 40:48.513
I give it to you and say,
"Bye, money! Bye.

40:48.513 --> 40:49.580
I'll never see you again."
Right.

40:49.580 --> 40:51.749
I'm sorry, guys.
I'm out.

40:51.749 --> 40:52.850
-Thank you.
-Good luck, guys.

40:52.850 --> 40:53.952
Cuban: Congrats
on what you've accomplished.

40:53.952 --> 40:55.553
All right, well, I think
you guys missed out

40:55.553 --> 40:57.422
